\begin_layout Plain Layout

Once your code works on your machine,
 the next challenge is getting it to work on someone else’s.
 This involves two things:
 managing your internal code structure (Packages) and bundling your application for the world (Publishing).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{The Internal Structure:
 Packages}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

As we touched on in Chapter 9,
 packages are the "folders" of your logic.
 They prevent name collisions and organize your code into logical domains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

package io.startup.renaissance.auth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

class Authenticator:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  def login() = ???
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

The 
\backslash
textbf{Pragmatic} rule:
 Your package names should usually mirror your folder structure (e.g.,
 
\backslash
texttt{src/auth/Authenticator.scala}),
 making it easy for developers to find files just by looking at the import statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{The project.scala File:
 The Source of Truth}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Instead of scattering settings across multiple files,
 we centralize everything in 
\backslash
texttt{project.scala}.
 This is your manifest.
 It tells 
\backslash
texttt{scala-cli} who you are,
 what version you’re on,
 and what you need.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

//> using scala "3.3.1"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

//> using dep "com.softwaremill.sttp.client3::core:3.9.0"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

//> using dep "org.tpolecat::doobie-core:1.0.0-RC4"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

// Publishing metadata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

//> using publish.name "renaissance-core"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

//> using publish.organization "io.startup"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

//> using publish.version "0.1.0"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Creating an Executable (Fat JARs)}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

The most common way to share a Scala app is a "Fat JAR" (or Assembly).
 This is a single file that contains your code 
\backslash
textbf{plus} every library it needs to run (like 
\backslash
texttt{sttp} and 
\backslash
texttt{Doobie}).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

scala-cli package .
 --assembly -o renaissance.jar
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Now,
 anyone with a JVM can run your app with:
 
\backslash
texttt{java -jar renaissance.jar}.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Native Binaries:
 No JVM Required}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

For CLI tools where you want "instant-on" performance,
 you can package your app as a native binary.
 This uses GraalVM to compile your Scala code down to machine code (like C++ or Go).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

scala-cli package .
 --native-image -o renaissance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

This produces a file that runs natively on the target OS,
 with no Java installation required by the end-user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Publishing to the World}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

If you’ve built a library that others should use,
 you’ll want to "publish" it to a repository (like Maven Central or a private GitHub Packages repo).
 
\backslash
texttt{scala-cli} makes this surprisingly simple:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{verbatim}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# This prepares your library for a repository
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

scala-cli publish .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{verbatim}
\end_layout

